The **Ninetieth Minnesota Legislature** is the current
[legislature](/wiki/Legislature "Legislature") of the [U.S.
state](/wiki/U.S._state "U.S. state") of [Minnesota](/wiki/Minnesota
"Minnesota"). It is composed of the [Minnesota Senate](/wiki/Minnesota_Senate
"Minnesota Senate") and the [Minnesota House of
Representatives](/wiki/Minnesota_House_of_Representatives "Minnesota House of
Representatives"), based on the results of the [2016 Senate
election](/wiki/Minnesota_Senate_election,_2016 "Minnesota Senate election,
2016") and the [2016 House
election](/wiki/Minnesota_House_of_Representatives_election,_2016 "Minnesota
House of Representatives election, 2016"). It convened in [Saint
Paul](/wiki/Saint_Paul,_Minnesota "Saint Paul, Minnesota") on January 3, 2017
and will end its biennial session on January 7, 2019. The legislature's 2017
session ended on May 22, 2017, and reconvened on February 20, 2018.[1] The
legislature will adjourn no later than May 21, 2018, as mandated by the
[Minnesota Constitution](/wiki/Minnesota_Constitution "Minnesota
Constitution"). A special session to complete unfinished budget-related
business was held from May 23 to 26, 2017.[2]

## Major
events[[edit](/w/index.php?title=90th_Minnesota_Legislature&action=edit&section=1
"Edit section: Major events")]

  * January 23, 2017: [Governor](/wiki/List_of_Governors_of_Minnesota "List of Governors of Minnesota") [Mark Dayton](/wiki/Mark_Dayton "Mark Dayton") delivered his 2017 [State of the State](/wiki/State_of_the_State_address "State of the State address") address before a joint legislative session. Nearing the end of his speech, Dayton collapsed and was attended to by, among others, state senators and physicians [Scott Jensen](/wiki/Scott_Jensen_\(Minnesota_politician\) "Scott Jensen \(Minnesota politician\)") and Matt Klein.[3][4]
  * February 22, 2017: A joint legislative session was held to elect regents of the [University of Minnesota](/wiki/University_of_Minnesota_system "University of Minnesota system").[5]
  * March 14, 2018: Governor Dayton delivered his 2018 State of the State address before a joint legislative session.[6]

## Summary of
actions[[edit](/w/index.php?title=90th_Minnesota_Legislature&action=edit&section=7
"Edit section: Summary of actions")]

In this Legislature, all acts have been approved (signed) by
[Governor](/wiki/Governor_of_Minnesota "Governor of Minnesota") [Mark
Dayton](/wiki/Mark_Dayton "Mark Dayton"), with the notable exceptions of H.F.
No. 809, an act that would prohibit public funding of abortion; H.F. No. 812,
an act that would require facilities that perform abortions to be licensed; a
first set of acts appropriating money for the state budget; H.F. No. 4, the
first omnibus tax act; H.F. No. 140, an act that would change how public
school teachers are licensed; and 2017, First Special Session S.F. No. 3, an
act that would most notably prohibit local governments from setting a higher
minimum wage and requiring benefits for private sector employees than what is
required by law, all of which were [vetoed](/wiki/Veto "Veto"). In Laws 2017,
First Special Session chapter 4, the omnibus state government appropriations
act, two appropriations for the Senate and the House of Representatives were
[line-item vetoed](/wiki/Line-item_veto_in_the_United_States "Line-item veto
in the United States"). Chapter 13, the reinsurance act, became law without
the governor's signature.

In total, 18 acts have been vetoed—including one from the 2017, First Special
Session, two items of appropriation in one act from the 2017, First Special
Session have been line-item vetoed, and two acts have become law without the
governor's signature.[45] No acts or items have been enacted by the
Legislature over the governor's veto. After the adjournment of the First
Special Session, legislative leaders sued Governor Dayton over the validity of
his line-item vetoes for legislative appropriations. The ensuing court case,
_[Ninetieth Minnesota State Senate v.
Dayton](/wiki/Ninetieth_Minnesota_State_Senate_v._Dayton "Ninetieth Minnesota
State Senate v. Dayton")_ , proceeded to the [Minnesota Supreme
Court](/wiki/Minnesota_Supreme_Court "Minnesota Supreme Court"); the Court
upheld the Governor's vetoes.[46]
